#compdef trekker
# =============================================================================
# trekker — Omercan Balandi (obsfx)'s "A CLI-based
#           issue tracker built for AI coding agents.
#           Stores tasks, epics, and dependencies in
#           a local SQLite database" — a TypeScript /
#           Bun CLI that lets autonomous coding agents
#           (Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, OpenHands,
#           Aider) manage their own work items
#           through a local SQLite database without
#           round-trips to GitHub Issues / Linear /
#           Jira REST APIs.  Provides epic + task +
#           subtask + comment + dependency tracking
#           plus search + history + readiness
#           checking, all via a structured CLI an
#           LLM can invoke deterministically.
#           Distinguishing from GitHub Issues CLI
#           (`gh issue`), Linear CLI (commercial),
#           Jira CLI (`jira` from go-jira), Forge
#           Agentic Coding CLI, and various agentic-
#           memory systems (claude-mem, vibe-log at
#           R699) by:
#             - DRIZZLE-ORM SQLITE STORAGE — uses
#               Drizzle Team's drizzle-orm (this is
#               the headline CLI library that closes
#               Axis 35 on the TS-Node side; see
#               taxonomy notes below) with SQLite as
#               the storage backend; all data lives
#               in `.trekker/db.sqlite` in the project
#               directory
#             - DRIZZLE-KIT MIGRATION — uses drizzle-
#               kit for schema migrations; `npm run
#               db:generate` + `db:migrate` are the
#               dev workflow for schema evolution
#             - 14-COMMAND TREE — init, wipe, epic,
#               task, subtask, comment, dep,
#               quickstart, seed, search, history,
#               list, ready, config.  Each command
#               has its own subcommands (e.g., `task
#               add`, `task list`, `task done`)
#             - TOON OUTPUT FORMAT — `--toon` flag
#               emits results in TOON format (a YAML-
#               adjacent format optimized for LLM
#               consumption with predictable
#               indentation + key ordering); useful
#               for piping into agentic workflows
#             - QUICKSTART WIZARD — `trekker
#               quickstart` is the onboarding wizard
#               that creates a starter epic + sample
#               tasks + dependencies in one
#               invocation
#             - SEED MODE — `trekker seed` populates
#               the DB with example data for testing
#               + agent training
#             - SEARCH — `trekker search <query>`
#               full-text searches across task +
#               epic + comment text using SQLite's
#               built-in LIKE matching (no FTS5
#               currently)
#             - HISTORY — `trekker history` shows the
#               audit log of changes (every task
#               mutation records a history entry)
#             - DEPENDENCY GRAPH — `trekker dep`
#               manages task dependencies; `trekker
#               ready` shows tasks whose dependencies
#               are met + are eligible to start now
#               (essential for parallel agent
#               coordination)
#             - LOCAL-FIRST — no network calls; the
#               SQLite database is the single source
#               of truth.  AI agents can manage tasks
#               offline without needing API tokens or
#               internet access
#             - BUN-NATIVE BUILD — `bun build` packages
#               the CLI; runs on Bun + Node.js (Node
#               requires --import bun-types or similar
#               polyfill)
#             - COMMANDER CLI — uses commander 13.x
#               (Axis 1 argparse covered) for the
#               command tree
#             - AI-AGENT-FIRST UX — flag names + output
#               formats deliberately chosen for LLM
#               readability (e.g., short flag names,
#               consistent JSON-or-TOON output, no
#               interactive prompts in the default
#               flow)
#           Used by: developers running autonomous
#           coding agents that need persistent task
#           memory + planning state across invocations,
#           agentic-AI researchers building multi-
#           agent task coordination, and individual
#           developers wanting a lightweight local-
#           first task manager that doubles as an LLM
#           tool provider.
#
# Author:  Omercan Balandi (obsfx on GitHub).  License:
